<HEADLINE> Zairean Parties Urged to ensure Free Access to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Aid agencies in eastern Zaire
have called on warring parties in the Great Lakes region to
provide free access to refugees and displaced persons and enable
aid workers to assist them.
</P>
<P>
A joint statement by aid agencies reaching here today said
that "these people's needs must not be overlooked as the Zairean
parties prepare for political negotiations over their country's
future."
</P>
<P>
As representatives of the Zairean government and rebels
prepare to meet in South Africa, the release said, "we appeal to
the participants in the talks to fully consider the urgent
humanitarian needs" of refugees stranded in the war zone.
</P>
<P>
The release noted that hundreds of thousands of refugees fled
into the rain forest to escape the fighting and violence in
eastern Zaire.
trying to aid more than
100,000 refugees who have re-emerged from the forest, the release
said, noting that many thousands of Rwandan and Burundi refugees
remain out of reach.
</P>
<P>
Following the seizure of Zaire's third largest city of
Kisangani late last month, rebels led by Laurent Kabila gave
order to refugees living around the city to leave their temporary
camps.
</P>
<P>
Since then, hundreds of thousands of refugees trapped in the
Zaire jungle near a railway line could die any timei unless aid
workers provide food, water and medicine to them, said the
release.
</P>
<P>
The joint statement was issued by European Union Commission
for Humanitarian Aid, U.N. High Commission for Refugees, UNICEF
and WFP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
