<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia to Mobilize Resources Against Epidemics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Minister of Health
Adem Ibrahim said that Ethiopia is ready to mobilize its
resources in renewed efforts to curb the widespread "emergence
and re-emergence of infectious epidemics" in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Adem said Ethiopia should give top priority to the development
of national capacity in the area of epidemiological serveillance
and control of epidemics.
</P>
<P>
The remark were made by the minister to mark World Health Day
to be observed throughout the world on April 7, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Adem put particular stress on hiv/aids, which causes human
suffering and economic burden to society, the terrible ebola
epidemic which broke out in Zaire in 1994, a new form of cholera
(bloody diarrhoae) as some of the newly detected infectious
diseases that are of global concern.
</P>
<P>
The minister also indicated that tuberculosis together with
its association with hiv infection, cholera which has been
reintroduced into countries where it had once disappeared, lassa
fever and yellow fever outbreaks, the meningococcal meningitis
pandemic which, with its "unprecedented gravity" occurred in west
Africa to spread from its usual zone (the meningitis belt) into
central and southern africa, have reappeared in epidemic
proportions due in part to the deterioration in water and
sanitation systems.
</P>
<P>
He attributed several factors including rapid and intense
international travels, urban overcrowding with poor sanitation,
and deteriorating public health infrastructure which has
increasingly become unable to cope with increasing demands of the
population to the emergence and re-emergence of infectious
diseases.
</P>
<P>
The theme of this year's World Health Day is "emerging
infectious diseases -- global alert, global response". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
