<DOCNO> XIE19970407.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Official Sets Conditions Resumption of Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 6 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) said today that the
Palestinians are willing to resume political contacts with Israel
on the condition that Israel freezes all Jewish settlement
activities.
</P>
<P>
During an interview with Israel Radio, Saeb Erekat, PNA's
Local Government Minister and top negotiator, said that Israeli
Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu should stop his accusation of
the Palestinians, adding it was Netanyahu's policy which helped
Palestinian extremists and threw the peace process into the
current crisis.
</P>
<P>
Erekat stressed that the PNA has been making every responsible
effort to fight against terrorists, and would not tolerate any
violent acts against the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ahmed Tibi, adviser to PNA President Yasser Arafat,
told Israel Radio that there is no reason for Arafat not to meet
with Netanyahu, if there is an Israeli commitment to freezing
settlement activities.
</P>
<P>
Tibi said that the Palestinians will agree to begin
negotiations on a permanent status agreement with Israel, if
the Interim Agreement, which calls for further Israeli pullback
from the West Bank, is also implemented.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that the PNA will not agree to bypass what should
be implemented under the Interim Agreement before talks begin on a
final status accord between Israel and the PNA.
</P>
<P>
In earlier March, Netanyahu proposed to conduct and
"accelerate" the final status talks with the Palestinians, which
would hopefully be completed within six months, without exceeding
nine months at the latest.
</P>
<P>
Palestinians rejected the proposal and insisted that Israel
first implement the Interim Agreement, also known as Oslo II.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's timetable is quite ambitious, since the issues in the
final status talks, such as the status of Jerusalem, borders
and settlements, are at the heart of the Israeli-Palestinian
conflict.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, it took four months of intensive negotiations
between the two sides just to deal with a pullback from 80
percent of the West Bank town of Hebron. 
</P>
</TEXT>
