<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's Labor Party U-turns on Privatization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Britain's opposition Labor Party,
facing a general election on May 1, will break with its
traditional commitment to nationalization and embrace a policy of
privatization, local press reports said today.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Labor leader Tony Blair will tell
businessmen in a speech on Monday that if his party comes to
office after the election, it will endorse the privatization
strategy and will sell off billions of pounds-worth of state
assets.
</P>
<P>
Blair will say that his government's "presumption should be
that economic activity is best left to the private sector, with
market forces being encouraged to operate".
</P>
<P>
Shadow chancellor Gordon Brown this week will also announce
Labor's conversion to the policy of privatization which the ruling
Conservative Party has pursued successfully over the past 18
years.
</P>
<P>
If Labor wins, Brown will conduct an urgent review of all
government services, land and buildings with the aim of selling
assets worth billions of pounds.
</P>
<P>
Analysts saw the move as the Labor Party's effort to head off
further damaging Tory attacks in the general election campaign.
</P>
<P>
The Conservatives had claimed that a Labor government would be
left with a 12 billion pounds (19.7 billion US dollars) "black
hole" in its income, which would include missing revenue from Tory
privatization.  
</P>
</TEXT>
