<HEADLINE> Five WNBF Leaders Detained </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Five of the sixteen high command
members of the West Nile Bank Front (WNBF) including its deputy
commander have been detained in southern Sudan, "the New Vision"
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Abdallatif Tiyoa, the deputy overall commander of WNBF, and
Juma Musa Degga, the advisor of the main leader of WNBF and their
three colleaqgues, gave interviews to Emmy Allio, a reporter of
the newspaper in the city of Yei in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The five were captured by Sudan People's Liberation Army
(SPLA) in an ambush on March 12 in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
This was the first report of the numbers and the identities of
the captured leaders of WNBF. Uganda media earlier referred the
loss of WNBF leadership in southern Sudan as mostly "killed or
captured".
</P>
<P>
Among the 16 high commander members of WNBF, only two
including Juma Oris survived the ambush and fled to Kartoum, the
capital of Sudan, the report said, adding that six were missing
since the operation, two others were killed in the fierce
fighting with their 800 soldiers, and still another has been
killed in eastern Zaire on March 9.
</P>
<P>
WNBF lost its main forces in the battle, earlier reports said.
The five rebel leaders were captured with their 500 subordinates.
</P>
<P>
Juma Oris agreed to form a joint rebel group with the Lord
Resistance Army (LRA) last week, an earlier report said.
</P>
<P>
There were three main rebel groups in Uganda: WNBF active in
the north-west, Lra in the north and Allied Democratic Forces
(ADF) in the west. The Uganda National Rescue Front (UNRF, part
two), another small rebel group active in the north-west, was in
contact with Lra to form a joint rebel group earlier.
</P>
<P>
lra had some 2,000 soldiers in previous years. But it has only
three detachments with some 200 men each now.
</P>
<P>
Adf had some 1,000 men in its ranks last November. But its
main forces were annihilated by Uganda army later and its
remaining forces devided into some small groups scattered in the
west and the south-west. Recent reports from the west said some
700 defeated Zairean government troops joined its ranks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
