<HEADLINE> Makwetu Suspended as PAC Leader of S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Former Pan African Congress
(PAC) leader Clarence Makwetu has been suspended from his
leadership position in the party, a PAC spokeswoman said today.
</P>
<P>
However, Makwetu will remain a member of parliament pending
the second round of disciplinary steps against him, the
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
This decision was made by the PAC National Executive
Committee, which met in Johannesburg on Saturday to consider
Makwetu's future in the party, she said.
</P>
<P>
The PAC is one of the major political organizations of the
South African black people.
</P>
<P>
Makwetu was given the newly created post of chairman after he
lost the presidency to former Methodist Church leader Bishop
Stanley Mogoba at a national congress in December last year.
</P>
<P>
Makwetu was charged with violating the PAC's Constitution by
allegedly dividing the party, creating factions and undermining
leadership.
</P>
<P>
He failed to appear before a disciplinary committee in
Pretoria on Thursday, which went ahead with proceedings in his
absence.
</P>
<P>
However, insiders said the disciplinary committee decided that
in the interests of transparency and to counter accusations from
supporters that Makwetu had been prejudiced, he would be given a
final opportunity to present his case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
