<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zairean Peace Talks to Be More Structured, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Peace talks between the
Zairean government and the anti-government armed forces would
resume on a more structured basis in Pretoria today, the South
African Press Association (SAPA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
Discussion between the two parties so far had been of an
informal nature, Spokesman for the South African Foreign Ministry
Pieter Swanepoel was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"They only exchanged ideas on the informal basis on Saturday
as they were still waiting for all the delegates to arrive,"
Swanepoel said, adding that the more structured talks will start
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Swanepoel declined to disclose the venue of the secret talks.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations to find a peaceful resolution for the ongoing
Zairean civil war formally kicked off in Pretoria, the
administrative capital of South Africa on Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Chief negotiators from the Zairean government and the
anti-government forces led by Laurent Kabila have reportedly
committed themselves to seeking a negotiated settlement.
</P>
<P>
However, a Zairean Embassy spokesman on Sunday expressed fears
that the current situation in Zaire might not be conducive to
successful talks.
</P>
<P>
He said attempts by a coalition of opposition parties to
remove recently appointed Prime Minister Etienne Tshisekedi could
jeopardise the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is hosting the talks as one of four countries
chosen at a summit in Nairobi last December to spearhead peace
efforts in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, who had played a
prominent role as broker, said yesterday that the coming
negotiations would be co-chaired by South African Deputy Foreign
Minister Aziz Pahad and Mohamed Sahnoun, special representative
of the United Nations for the Great Lakes Region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
