<HEADLINE> Iranian Population Growth Down to 1.6 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Iran claimed here today that
its population growth rate dropped down to 1.6 percent during
the last Iranian year which ended on March 20, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Ali Reza Marandi, Minister of Health and Medical Care, said
that the decelerating population growth rate is expected to
continue during the current Iranian year.
</P>
<P>
The state-run Tehran Radio reported that the health minister
made the remarks on the occasion of the International Health
Day, an event that was also attended by President Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
However, some specialists maintained that Iran's population
policy is not so successful as the government claimed. They said
that the population growth rate is around 1.8-2.0 percent in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The population growth rate stood at 3.2 percent on average
during the 10-year period from 1976 to 1986.
</P>
<P>
The assessment of Iran's population is also different between
specialists and the government. The U.N. population specialists
estimated the Iranian population at 65 million while the government
said that it is less then 60 million at present.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian health minister said that his country has also
made progress in reducing the mortality rate of mothers, which
dropped from 254 per 100,000 18 years ago to 40 per 100,000 now.
</P>
</TEXT>
