<HEADLINE> Egypt Detains 27 Brotherhood Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian State Security Prosecutor
General Hesham Saraya has ordered the imprisonment of 27 members
of the outlawed Muslim Brotherhood for 15 days pending
investigations, the Egyptian MENA news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
These people, arrested during a meeting in the Giza province
outside of Cairo on Saturday, are mainly accused of joining an
outlawed group and distributing leaflets in an anti-government
campaign to shake national security.
</P>
<P>
Investigations began Saturday night on the arrested group,
which includes five journalists and a lawyer. The rest were
reportedly government employees.
</P>
<P>
The Muslim Brotherhood, Egypt's largest outlawed fundamentalist
group, is accused of backing the violent militant campaign against
the government since 1992 to establish a strict Islamic rule and
is officially banned.
</P>
<P>
The government stroke hard on the Brotherhood in 1995 when
hundreds of its members were arrested and dozens tried before
special military tribunals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
