<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli FM Denies Reports Of US Pressure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy said today that the U.S. is not exerting heavy pressure on
Israel to freeze settlements, reported the state-run Israel TV.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. opposition to settlement activities is known, Levy
told reporters before meeting with Miguel Moratinos, European
Union (EU) Special Envoy to the Middle East Peace Process.
</P>
<P>
The minister also dismissed a suggestion that Israel and the
U.S. are moving on a collision course due to the Israeli
government's settlement policy.
</P>
<P>
Speculations were widely spread about U.S. pressure on Israel
as Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu left Israel this morning for
urgent meetings with U.S. President Bill Clinton and Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is expected to present Netanyahu a proposal to solve
the crisis in the Israeli-Palestinian relations and get the
stalled peace process back on track. But U.S. officials remain
tight-lipped over the content of the proposal to be offered
during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
According to a report from Washington, Clinton is likely to
put pressure on Netanyahu to halt the construction of the Jewish
settlement at Har Homa in East Jerusalem, as well as on
Palestinians to stop violence and combat terrorism.
</P>
<P>
During his two-day working visit, Netanyahu will also visit
King Hussein of Jordan, who is receiving medical treatment in a
U.S. hospital. The king urged Clinton to enhance his role in
mediating the endangered peace process during his meeting with
the president in Washington last week.
</P>
<P>
Palestinians President Yasser Arafat has sent Minister of
Higher Education Hanan Ashrawi to Washington, where she will
meet with Albright and Middle East peace coordinator Dennis
Ross after Clinton-Netanyahu summit Monday.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Levy, Moratinos put forward new ideas
for reviving the peace process. Levy said that Europe is
welcome to provide help and advice, but cannot replace the
U.S. in the peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Since this year, the EU has stepped up its diplomatic
activities to assert its role in the peace process in the adjacent
Middle East. Moratinos has shuffled between Israel and its Arab
neighbors for the past weeks. He is scheduled to return to
Brussels Monday for a special meeting of EU Middle East experts.
</P>
<P>
France is also reportedly planning to raise a new proposal
to break the deadlock of the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
