<HEADLINE> Zaire Peace Talks Continue Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Representatives of the
Zairean government and rebels were still locked in peace talks in
Pretoria today in an attempt to find a lasting solution to the
on-going conflict in their country.
</P>
<P>
South African Foreign Affairs Ministry spokesman Pieter Swanepoel
said at a media briefing that the talks, which began yesterday at an
undisclosed venue in Pretoria, resumed in a more structured fashion
this morning.
</P>
<P>
Swanepoel did not say, however, whether the talks would
continue tomorrow. He also declined to reveal anything about the
substance of the present negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Today's talks were co-chaired by South African Deputy Foreign
Affairs Minister Aziz Pahad and United Nations' special envoy for
the Great Lakes region Mohamed Sahnoun.
</P>
<P>
Delegations at the talks were led by Zairean Foreign Minister
Kamanda wa Kamanda and special envoy of rebel leader Laurent
Kabila Bizima Karaha.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is hosting the Zairean peace talks as one of the four
countries chosen at a Nairobi summit last December to spearhead peace
efforts in the war-torn Zaire.
</P>
<P>
However, South African officials have consistently declined to
provide details about the on-going talks, saying it was up to the
negotiating parties to give out such information. enditem

