<HEADLINE> Mozambique Urged to Observe Shrimp-fishing Quota </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 6 (Xinhua) -- The National Fishery Research
Institute of Mozambique has accused the Mozambican government of
not observing the shrimp fishing quota of 6,000 tons for 1996,
the Mozambique Information Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to a news release issued here today by the
institute, Mozambique's actual catch of shrimps reached 8,000 tons
in 1996, well surpassing the quota of 6,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
It urged the Mozambican government to observe the fishing
quota for sustained development of crustacean resources.
</P>
<P>
This year's fishing quota of shrimps, approved by the
Mozambican government, is 7,600 tons, the release added.
</P>
<P>
Shrimps accounted for 77 percent of the exported aquatic
products of Mozambique in 1996, which earned the country 72
million US Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
