<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-06 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait, Malaysia Sign Agreement to Avoid Double </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait and Malaysia signed
here today an agreement to avoid double taxation in a bid to
further boost trade between the two Islamic countries.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Kuwaiti Deputy Prime Minister and
Finance Minister Nasser Abdullah Al-Rudhan and Malaysian
Entrepreneur Development Minister Mustapha Mohamed, who is
accompanying Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad on a three
day visit to Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir, who arrived here Saturday, was on his first visit to
Kuwait after taking office as Malaysian premier in 1981.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's Amir Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah met Mahathir this
morning and honored him with Mubarak the Great Medal in
"appreciation for Mahathir's significant efforts for enhancing ties
of brotherhood and cooperation between the two Muslim countries
and brotherly peoples," official sources said.
</P>
<P>
During Mahathir's visit, Kuwait's acting Prime Minister and
Foreign Minister Sheikh Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Jaber Al-Sabah held
talks with Mahathir on promoting bilateral ties between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait and Malaysia have historic political and economic
relations, and diplomatic ties was established between them far
back to 1963.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's trade with Kuwait last year totaled 296 million
ringgit (118.4 million U.S. dollars), according to figures
available from Malaysian Embassy in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Statistics reported by official Kuwait News Agency showed that
Malaysian exports to Kuwait were estimated at around 68 million
U.S. dollars in 1995 compared to around 60.7 million U.S. dollars
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia was ranked 18 among Kuwaiti trade partners in 1995
with its exports to Kuwait reaching to nearly 1.31 percent of
total Kuwaiti imports, while Malaysian imports of oil and its
derivatives from Kuwait amounted to 15 percent of its total
consumption.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Kuwait Finance House signed in Malaysia a deal
valued at 100 million U.S. dollars with Malaysian city of
Bank-Labuan to finance the purchase of fuel and plane spare parts
for the Malaysian Airlines Company.
</P>
<P>
After wrapping up his three day visit to Kuwait Monday,
Mahathir will travel to Bahrain to continue his Gulf tour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
