<HEADLINE> France Calls for EU Initiative on Middle East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 6 (Xinhua) -- France has called on the 15 European
Union (EU) nations to make an initiative to contribute to the
unjamming of the peace process between Israel and Palestinians,
reported the Agence France-Presse.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Herve de Charette today said at an EU
foreign ministers' meeting in the Dutch city Noordwijk that the
current president of EU, the Netherlands, should send a message to
the United States President Bill Clinton on the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the Dutch presidency of the European Union send
a message to President Clinton suggesting the (two) sides fix the
basis for a new departure to put an end to the impasse of the
peace process," said de Charette.
</P>
<P>
He said that the basis for a new departure of the peace process
should be built on the commitment by Israel and Palestinians to
respect the agreements of Oslo and Madrid, and an ending by Israel
of its blockade of the Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
The suspension of the construction of a new Jewish settlement
in Har Homa district of East Jerusalem by Israel, suspension of
confiscation of identity cards of Palestinians in Jerusalem by
Israel, and a commitment by Palestinians to fight terrorism should
also be the basis for relaunching the peace process, said de
Charette.
</P>
<P>
The French proposal will be discussed by EU foreign ministers
this evening in Noordwijk, and again by the EU foreign ministry
officials in charge of the Middle East on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benyamin Netanyahu is on a visit in
Washington to discuss with President Clinton his plan to relaunch
peace talks with the Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
