<HEADLINE> UK Issues Guidelines for Magistrates on Traffic Offenders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Motorists in Britain who confess to
speeding or drink-driving offenses immediately are to have their
punishment cut by a third.
</P>
<P>
This is one of the main instructions to magistrates in new
guidelines issued in an attempt to standardize sentencing all over
the country.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines, produced by the Magistrates' association with
the Justice's Clerk Society, give courts charts to help them to
decide on the appropriate level of fines and jail. According to
the offender's level of income -- low, average or high.
</P>
<P>
However, magistrates are not obliged to stick to the sentences
recommended -- and each of the 52 pages in the document bears the
sentence: "Remember: these are guidelines, not a tariff."
</P>
<P>
Under the guidelines, you will get three penalty points on your
driving license if, for instance, you are driving at up to 40mph
in an area with a 30mph limit.
</P>
<P>
You may also be fined 60 pounds (96 US dollars) if you are on a
low income, 150 pounds (240 US dollars) on an average income and
360 pounds (576 US dollars) on a high income.
</P>
<P>
Magistrates are offered a range of aggravating or mitigating
factors to take into account when passing sentence.
</P>
<P>
In the case of drink-driving offenses, the chart gives the rate
of alcohol on the breath, in the blood and in the urine related to
the length of disqualification and fine.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines urge: "consider mitigation, for example
cooperation with the police. Consider a discount for a timely
guilty plea."
</P>
<P>
The guidelines also list amounts of compensation which can be
awarded. A black eye, for instance, can earn the victim 100 pounds
(160 US dollars), while the loss of a front tooth carries a 1,000
pounds (1,600 US dollars) compensation award.  
</P>
</TEXT>
