<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Launches TB, Leprosy Prevention Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Health Minister
Adem Ibrahim today announced that an integrated tuberculosis (TB)
and leprosy prevention program has been launched across the
country.
</P>
<P>
Adem called for joint efforts of government and non-
government bodies, international organizations, donors,
religious leaders, professional associations and the private
sector in preventive campaigns against the diseases.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued in connection with the World Health Day
which falls on tomorrow, the minister said TB was reported last
year as "the first killer disease" while malaria and dysentery
were second and third respectively on the top ten list.
</P>
<P>
Although TB had never been put under control in the
country, it can be said that the disease gradually relapsed and
has now become a major killer disease after the AIDS virus came
into the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
A policy is being formulated with a view to involving
government, non-government bodies and donor organizations in the
anti-AIDS campaigns, the minister noted.
</P>
<P>
He added that malaria remains to be a major health problem in
the country as the disease has become resistant to curative and
preventive medicines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
