<HEADLINE> Egypt to Launch Medicine Week in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Egypt will kick off a Medicine Week
in Iraq Tuesday in a bid to export the goods to the country within
the framework of the oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
A large consignment of Egypt-made medicines reached the Iraqi
capital of Baghdad Saturday for the week-long fair, Ouny Hashem,
director of the Egyptian Trade Center in Iraq told the Egyptian
MENA news agency.
</P>
<P>
The exhibited products will be later offered free of charge to
the Iraqi people, he added.
</P>
<P>
On the sidelines of the fair, an Egyptian medical delegation
will hold rounds of meetings with Iraqi health ministry officials
to discuss its requirements of medicines, chemicals and medical
equipment.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will also work out a delivery schedule for these
goods, said Galal Ghorab, head of the Egyptian Holding Company for
Medicines, which is co-organizing the fair with the Iraqi health
ministry.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi leadership has given special directives to the health
ministry and pharmaceutical firms to obtain medicine from Egypt in
particular, according to Ghorab.
</P>
<P>
The event is designed to get acquainted with Iraq's pressing
needs for drug since the UN-imposed economic sanctions on Iraq were
partially removed late last year.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 20 Egyptian firms specialized in manufacturing of
drug will participate in the show.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed in late January, Egypt will export 3
million U.S. dollars of medicine to Iraq. The first batch of the
medicine has already reached Iraq in late February.
</P>
<P>
Egypt expects the volume of exports to Iraq to reach 100
million U.S. dollars in the first six months of the implementation
of the oil-for-food deal concluded between the UN and Iraq last
December to ease the impact of the trade sanctions.
</P>
<P>
In line with the deal, Iraq will be allowed to sell 2 billion
dollars of oil in six months, 30 percent of which will be
funneled to the Fund for Gulf War Reparations and meeting other
UN costs.
</P>
<P>
Then it will have access to about 1.3 billion dollars over six
months to purchase food, medicine and other daily necessities,
which is much less than the annual 8 billion dollars it used to
buy food and medicine before the embargo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
