<HEADLINE> NPC Leader Thanks Italy for Geneva Stance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of China's National People's
Congress (NPC), Qiao Shi, said here today that he greatly
appreciated Italy's stance over the 53rd session of the United
Nations Commission on Human Rights, now under way in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
Qiao conveyed his gratitude during a meeting with Italian
Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini.
</P>
<P>
Dini said China has made great improvements in its human rights
record and Italy had decided to take a common stand with France,
Germany and Spain, and not to raise proposals against China at the
annual session of the Commission.
</P>
<P>
Qiao said it is pointless to make confrontations on human
rights issues in Geneva each year.
</P>
<P>
China supported dialogue and cooperation on human rights on the
basis of equality and mutual respect, and opposed confrontation,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Dini said Italy is enhancing ties with Asia-Pacific countries,
especially China, and the relations between Italy and China have
developed smoothly.
</P>
<P>
He said he had visited China twice and seen with his own eyes
great changes. It was a miracle for China to maintain rapid
economic growth while containing inflation, he said.
</P>
<P>
No other country could maintain such high economic growth for
such a long time, he added.
</P>
<P>
He hoped China would become a member of the World Trade
Organization as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Qiao said Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi's forthcoming
visit to China will further improve bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He said the two countries should push forward the bilateral
relations to usher in the 21st century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
