<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Reassures Strict Euro Criteria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 7 (Xinhua) -- German Finance Minister Theo Waigel
today rejected reports that he saw room for flexibility in
interpreting the strict budgetary requirements for joining the
single European currency, the Euro.
</P>
<P>
"Three is three.... There is no room for interpretation," said
Waigel.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to one of the five criteria under the
Maastricht Treaty which requires member states of the European
Union (EU) to cut their budget deficit to no higher than three
percent of the gross domestic product (GDP) in order to qualify
for Euro membership.
</P>
<P>
Press reports in leading British newspapers quoted Waigel as
saying, while attending a weekend meeting of EU finance ministers
in the Netherlands: "I have never nailed myself to the cross of
three percent".
</P>
<P>
It sparked speculation that Germany might retreat from its
hardline stance.
</P>
<P>
Given soaring jobless benefit costs caused by Germany's record
unemployment, there are growing doubts that Germany can make the
grade for the single currency on time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
