<HEADLINE> Ramos Cautious About Return of Former Military Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
here today parried criticisms on the government's cautious
handling of the return of former military chief Fabian Ver.
</P>
<P>
Ver was the chief of staff of the Philippine Armed Forces
during the regime of Ferdinand Marcos. He fled with Marcos in 1986
to the United States and recently asked for permission to go back
to the country.
</P>
<P>
"The crime (he committed) is very serious, we want to be sure,"
the president said after presenting as a guest of honor at the
opening ceremony of the First Asian Junior Badminton Championship.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said that the government is still in the process of
reviewing Ver's cases before the former military chief is allowed
to come home.
</P>
<P>
Ver faced criminal charges and would be arrested upon his
return to the country. However, some people, including Defense
Secretary Renato de Villa, said Ver's return will no longer pose
any threat to the national security.
</P>
<P>
Last week, former first lady and now Leyte Representative
Imelda Marcos asked the government to allow Ver to return to the
country so he can shed light on the assassination of former
opposition Senator Benigno Aquino, Jr.
</P>
<P>
Aquino was killed on August 2, 1983 upon his arrival at the
Manila International Airport after years of exile. Ver was one of
the accused but he was acquitted by the court.
</P>
<P>
Marcos named Ver as the chief of staff on August 15, 1981.
Although the term of office was only three years, Ver held the
position until he was forced to flee the country when the Marcos
regime was toppled in a people's uprising.  
</P>
</TEXT>
