<HEADLINE> China's Central Bank Improves State Sector Financial Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The People's Bank of China will
take steps to provide better financial services to state
enterprises this year to facilitate the nation's state-sector
reforms, a senior banking official said today.
</P>
<P>
"The central bank will double its effort this year to support
the restructuring and expansion of state enterprises," Chen Yuan,
the bank's deputy governor, said at a symposium on state
enterprise reforms in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Chen said a national information database for state enterprises
will be developed this year to help with management and
macro-economic controls.
</P>
<P>
The country will also try its sponsor bank system on a larger
scale, given its effectiveness in setting up a relatively stable
relationship between banks and enterprises and improving the
quality of credit with better supervision of borrowers'
performance, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
"Banks should provide active financial support to enterprises
with good economic returns, good market potentials and high credit
rating," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The banks also need to use their credit leverage more
effectively and more in line with state industrial policy, for a
more efficient distribution of state assets in various
industries," said Chen.
</P>
<P>
The deputy governor also called for further financial reforms,
saying that "the state-owned commercial banks should focus on
offering better services to state enterprises, and urban
development banks cater mainly to medium-sized and small firms."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
