<DOCNO> XIE19970407.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Urges U.N. Human Rights Body to Drop Cold War Thinking  (Part one) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It should reverse the present trend of politicizing human
rights issues and adopt correct guiding principles.
</P>
<P>
The alternative representative of the Chinese delegation, Wang
Guangya, was speaking at the 53rd session of the commission under
way in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
"With regard to the reform of the commission, priority should
be given to the elimination of Cold War thinking, the redress of
the currently prevailing trend of politicization and double
standards, and the establishment of the correct guiding
principles," he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged readjustment of the commission's membership to ensure
geographical balance.
</P>
<P>
"Reform of the commission should cover the issue of readjusting
its composition to ensure an equitable geographical distribution
of its membership. The Center for Human Rights should be
restructured according to the principle of transparency and
fairness," said Wang.
</P>
<P>
"For a long time, the group of developed countries has been
unduly over-represented in the commission. This phenomenon, which
is in serious violation of the principle of equitable geographical
distribution stipulated in the U.N. Charter, should be corrected
as soon as possible," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The Center for Human Rights is an important component of the
Commission on Human Rights. Smooth functioning of the commission
is inseparable from the support of the center," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the center will follow the principles of
transparency and fairness and refrain from deviating from its main
function of providing conference services and conducting research
work, " he said.
</P>
<P>
It was hoped that it would "attach genuine importance to the
right to development, correct the imbalance in the geographical
distribution of its staff members, and take effective measures to
redress the phenomena of severe lack of representation of Asian
countries in the center," he said.
</P>
<P>
He attacked the lack of democracy and equality in the
commission.
</P>
<P>
"Democracy is also indispensable in handling international
relations. It means that countries, big or small, strong or weak,
rich or poor, have the equal right to speech and the right to
choose their social systems and development paths. Their
sovereignty, cultures, traditions and values should be respected.
</P>
<P>
"However, some developed countries oppose such democracy in
international relations. They launch willful attacks on developing
countries, resort to sanctions from time to time and infringe upon
the democratic rights that other countries are entitled to. They
never examine or try to work on their own human rights problems,"
Wang complained.
</P>
<P>
"Sovereign equality is one of the important principles
enshrined in the U.N. Charter. Equality is the essence of human
rights. But it is difficult to understand why there is no
equality to speak of at the meetings of the commission.
</P>
<P>
"Over the past five years, 72 developing countries have been
subject to country resolutions due to manipulations of developed
countries. Name-calling of the former by the latter is also
frequent.
</P>
<P>
"Last year, in his statement on country human rights
situations, a representative from a certain group of developed
countries singled out more than 60 developing countries in one
breath.
</P>
<P>
"With regard to this kind of arrogance, this patronizing
attitude, this practice of picking on developing countries and
brandishing the baton of human rights against them demonstrated by
certain developed countries, we cannot but ask this question: Who
gave them the right to do so and do they, after all, have the
right to do so?
</P>
<P>
"Does the fact that they come from developed and well-off
countries give them the right to play judge before others and
teach others lessons as school-masters?
</P>
<P>
"In this commission, every member state is equal and there is
no such distinction between first-class and second-class
citizens. We sincerely hope that arrogance can be replaced by
genuine equality in international exchanges," Wang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970407.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
