<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Is Looking Forward To Chirac's Visit: Premier Says (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- In a meeting with French Defence
Minister Charles Millon today, China's Premier Li Peng said that
China is looking forward to President Jacques Chirac's visit to
Beijing in May, and said he believes the visit will produce
substantial results.
</P>
<P>
Li said that Chirac's visit is "a major event in Sino-French
relations," and that "we greatly appreciate President Chirac's
emphasis on relations with China and his devotion to Sino-French
friendly co-operation."
</P>
<P>
Recently, Chirac said that France will no longer support bills
against China at the UN human rights conference, Li noted, adding,
"We highly appreciate this wise and far-sighted decision, and
agree with President Chirac in his view that such actions against
China should be stopped."
</P>
<P>
Because countries differ in their national conditions, there
may be also differences in human rights conditions, the Premier
said, suggesting that they respect each other, reserve their
differences, and replace unpleasant confrontations with dialogue
on an equal footing.
</P>
<P>
"China will have various forms of communication and
co-operation with France on the protection and promotion of human
rights," he said.
</P>
<P>
Li said that in recent years bilateral relations have witnessed
overall progress. He also mentioned his visit to France last year,
and described a recent French visit by Qiao Shi, chairman of the
Standing Committee of the Chinese National People's Congress, as a
"great success."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970407.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Is Looking Forward to Chirac's Visit: Premier Says (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China and France, two countries with important responsibilities
in international affairs, both treasure their national
independence and share identical views on many important world
issues, Li said, pointing to the complementariness of their
economies and prospects for co-operation.
</P>
<P>
All this provides a solid base for friendly and
mutually-beneficial co-operation between the two countries, the
premier said.
</P>
<P>
As the world speeds up the pace of multi-polarization, Li said,
considering and handling bilateral relations from a strategic
standpoint, increasing consultation and co-operation, and
establishing friendly relations and cooperation for the 21st
century are not only in the interests of the people of the two
countries, but also benefit world peace, stability, and
development.
</P>
<P>
He said China is willing to join France in promoting world
peace and development, in compliance with the growing historical
trend of multi-polarization.
</P>
<P>
In expressing pleasure with his China visit, Millon said its
purpose is to promote communication between the two countries'
armed forces, reinforce bilateral co-operation, and push forward
economic, trade and technological contacts.
</P>
<P>
As permanent members of the UN Security Council, both France
and China have important responsibilities for world peace,
stability and economic progress, Million said. Since they both
advocate a multi-polar world, improvement of their friendly
relations will help accelerate the world's move towards this goal,
he added.
</P>
<P>
The two nations have much in common, and their co-operative
prospects in various fields are broad, Millon said, expressing the
belief that bilateral ties will develop through concerted efforts
by both sides.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of human rights, Millon said it is dialogue rather
than confrontation that conforms to the interest of all sides.
</P>
</TEXT>
