<DOCNO> XIE19970407.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Urges U.N. Human Rights Body to Drop Cold War Thinking  (Part Two) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He asked for dialogue instead of confrontation to solve
differences on human rights.
</P>
<P>
"It is justified that a country has its own focuses on the
promotion and protection of human rights, and takes appropriate
measures in light of its national conditions. It is also normal
and unavoidable that countries have some divergence of views on
human rights issues," Wang stressed.
</P>
<P>
"The correct way of handling such divergence is to engage in
dialogue and exchanges of views on the basis of mutual respect and
equality, rather than turning the commission into a courtroom and
adopting country resolutions against those countries which are not
to the liking of certain other countries.
</P>
<P>
"Such confrontation only leads to the escalation of hostility
and estrangement. It will not contribute to promoting, but to
blaspheming human rights," he commented.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese representative also criticized the commission for
unbalanced attention to civil and political rights and economic,
social and cultural rights.
</P>
<P>
"The phenomena of favoring civil and political rights and
slighting economic, social and cultural rights in the commission
should be redressed," he said.
</P>
<P>
"For a long time, some countries, in total disregard of the
integral whole of the concept of human rights, have ignored the
reality of severe poverty and famine in many developing countries,
and the fact that the poverty population of the whole world has
amounted to more than 1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
"They deny or downplay the importance of the realization of
economic, social, cultural rights and the right to development and
propagate the idea that civil and political rights are tantamount
to the right to development."
</P>
<P>
Wang pointed out: "In terms of the establishment of agenda
items, allocation of time, the number of resolutions adopted and
the establishment of rapporteurs, the importance received by
economic, social and cultural rights in the commission is far from
being proportional.
</P>
<P>
"The Center for Human Rights also fails to give adequate
attention to the right to development in its institutional
arrangement and resource allocation.
</P>
<P>
"This commission should take measures to correct its practice
of slighting economic, social and cultural rights and the right to
development," he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the work of the rapporteurs and the working groups
of the commission, Wang said: "Activities of the working groups
and the rapporteurs of the commission should be carried out in
line with established standards.
</P>
<P>
"They are to function under the supervision of the commission
and they are not human rights judges. Their work should be carried
out according to established rules. Their research, visits and
investigation activities should be done in such a way so as not to
infringe upon the sovereignty, dignity and interests of host
countries.
</P>
<P>
"Meanwhile, since they are directly involved in the
implementation of the decisions of the commission, the importance
of their work requires that their normal work should receive the
support and cooperation from all governments," Wang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
