<HEADLINE> Factions Against Aidid to Set up Government of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The first congress by the
factions opposing Hussein Mohamed Aidid in north Mogadishu has
endorsed the convening of so-called a national reconciliation
conference in northeastern port town Bosasso on June 10.
</P>
<P>
The conference, which is to end Tuesday, made a resolution
under which the Bosasso meeting will erect a Somali government of
national unity.
</P>
<P>
Somali women groups, intellectuals, religious scholars and the
traditional leaders will participate in the Bosasso meeting, said
the resolution.
</P>
<P>
About 1000 delegates from 31 of all the 41 factions that
formed the National Salvation Council (NSC) in Sodare, Ethiopia,
attended the conference starting Friday.
</P>
<P>
The conference which was earlier scheduled to conclude today
has been extended due to the debate over how the future
parliament of Somalia should be.
</P>
<P>
Some of the delegates who attended the meeting suggested that
the future parliament members should come from regions and
districts throughout the country while some proposed parliament
members should be selected on basis of tribal schemes.
</P>
<P>
Somalia's leading figures such as Osman Hassan Ali Atto and
Colonel Abndullahi Yussuf Ahmed of Habar Gidir and Majerten
clans failed to attend the conference.
</P>
<P>
The conference discussed the formation of a national force for
Somalia to implement the agreements reached at the conference.
</P>
<P>
Commander of the future forces of the Soldare group General
Mohamed Nur Galal, proposed that three types of forces need to be
legalized including strong military, policemen and the anarchy
formed militiamen who need extra care and demobilization.
</P>
<P>
North Mogadishu faction leader Ali Mahdi Mohamed, said at the
conference today that the talks between his delegates and those
of Hussein Mohamed Aidid over political end to conflict and
pacifying Mogadishu is making a tangible progress.
</P>
<P>
Ali Mahdi said he is optimistic about the outcome of the talks
which he said will be of use for all the Somalis and people in
Mogadishu in particular.
</P>
<P>
During the four-day conference, the EU special envoy to
Somalia Sigurd Illing, has discussed with others at the
conference about the humanitarian issues and the security of
Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
In his meetings with Ali Mahdi and Aidid separately, Illing
reiterated the need for a real reconciliation within the Somalis.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from different social groups and dignitaries also
attended the conference which was heavily guarded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
