<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Strengthen Prevention of Infectious Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- China should strengthen the
prevention and treatment of Infectious diseases which have
reappeared and pose a new threat to the nation's health in spite
of effective controls that China has developed, a health official
said today.
</P>
<P>
"Although the incidence and mortality rate of infectious
diseases has been dropping in general, we shouldn't slack off in
disease prevention and control," Public Health Minister Chen
Minzhang told a meeting in Beijing today for "World Health Day."
</P>
<P>
More than 1.84 million cases of infectious diseases were
reported in China last year, and 3,127 people died of them, Chen
said. The incidence rate was 154 per 100,000 people and mortality
25 per ten million people, both a drop of 7.18 percent from 1995,
he said.
</P>
<P>
However, China still has ten million people suffering from
hepatitis, and some 600,000 to one million newborn infants are
infected by Hepatitis B virus every year.
</P>
<P>
The country has more than six million tuberculosis patients,
including 1.5 million who are highly contagious, and plague and
cholera, which have been under effective control in recent
decades, have caused small-scale epidemics in some places in the
past few years, Chen noted, adding that "some new infectious
diseases have invaded the country and will probably cause
epidemics."
</P>
<P>
The number of people infected by HIV virus was more than 5,000
last October, but experts estimate that there are at least 50,000
to 100,000 HIV carriers in China at present.
</P>
<P>
Cases of colon bacillus, Lyme disease, and cholera have also
been found, according to a report released by the Ministry of
Public Health.
</P>
<P>
To meet this challenge, health departments will increase
surveillance and establish rapid prevention and containment
measures, the minister said, emphasizing that the ministry will
tighten controls on blood products and blood supplies in order to
prevent the transmission of Hepatitis C and G, HIV/AIDS, syphilis,
and malaria through tainted blood.
</P>
<P>
The theme of this year's World Health Day is "Emerging
Infectious Diseases -- Global Alert, Global Response." The World
Health Organization says that infectious diseases are a major
killer, and in the last two decades, more than 30 new, highly
contagious diseases have been identified, such as HIV/AIDS and the
Ebola virus. Diseases such as tuberculosis, diphtheria, cholera,
and dengue fever have also reappeared after recent declines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
