<HEADLINE> EU, Rio Group to Strengthen Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NOORDWIJK, Netherlands, April 7 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU)
and Latin American foreign ministers attending a ministerial
meeting here agree that the relations between the two blocs should
be further strengthened.
</P>
<P>
The two-day EU-Rio Group ministerial meeting, which opened here
on Monday, will focus on political developments in the EU and
Latin America, interregional cooperation, and the fight against
drugs, organized crime and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
European ministers will hold separate talks with their
counterparts in the Rio Group which is made up of Argentina,
Brazil, Uruguay, Paraguay, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru,
Venezuela, Chile, Mexico and Panama.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of EU troika (Ireland, the Netherlands
and Luxemburg) will hold talks with Mexico and Chile.
</P>
<P>
The EU and Mexico are currently trying to agree on a mandate
for wider economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, EU ministers will also hold talks with their
counterparts from the five Andean Community countries: Bolivia,
Colombia, Ecuador, Peru and Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
Their talks are expected to address the Andean Community's
political situation and the future evolution and EU-Andean
relations.
</P>
<P>
The EU-Andean Community links have been strengthened since 1990
as bilateral trade has increased. Bilateral trade rose to ECU 13.8
billion (15.7 billion U.S. dollars) in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The ties were further boosted by the growth of EU aid to the
region -- to ECU 150 million (171 million dollars) in 1995, 30
percent of it as assistance to Latin America -- and cooperation in
fighting drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Honduras attended the meeting as the observer from Central
America, and Guyana represented the Caribbean countries and
Caricom. 
</P>
