<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Set Up Group Homes for Working Disabled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysian government
plans to set up group homes for the disabled who can work and fend
for themselves, National Unity and Social Development Minister
Paduka Zaleha Ismail said today.
</P>
<P>
She said her ministry was prepared to extend the necessary
assistance to the Selangor and Federal Territory Mentally Retarded
Children Association which planned to run such homes for the
handicapped who could earn income and need not be dependent on
their parents and families for financial aid.
</P>
<P>
The homes could be set up in housing estates, not necessarily
in special buildings, to enable the disabled to interact with
local residents, the minister told reporters after presenting
certificates to teachers of mentally retarded children here.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the association, whose 100 mentally retarded
people secured permanent jobs, could negotiate with Kuala Lumpur
City Hall to acquire a few units of flats to convert them into
such homes.
</P>
<P>
There will be no age limit for occupants of the homes but they
must be able to work and foot their personal expenses including
house rent on their own, association president Fauziah Idris said
on the occasion.
</P>
<P>
She said there are 700 mentally retarded children from 12
schools under the association's purview.  
</P>
