<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Improve Treasury Bond Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- China will improve its treasury
bond marketing to increase liquidity and efficiency, according to
Gao Jian, director of the State Debt Mangement Department of the
Ministry of Finance.
</P>
<P>
"China will continue to standardize the market-oriented tender
approach in government bond floating," he said in a recent report,
noting that short-term discount bonds will be issued through
uniform price bids, while coupon bonds will be floated through
multi-price yield bids.
</P>
<P>
Both multi-price bids and uniform-price tenders will be used,
with the size to be based upon market demand.
</P>
<P>
The existing quotation subscription and bidding will be
replaced by competitive or non-competitive bidding, he said, and
that open bidding will be tried when necessary.
</P>
<P>
He noted that measures will also be taken to reduce the cost of
individual investors in opening a bond investment account to allow
them to buy certificate bonds more easily.
</P>
<P>
China should establish special funds for individual treasury
bond investment as soon as possible, Gao suggested, and that China
will issue government bonds more regularly to increase
predictability.
</P>
<P>
In his report, Gao also said that China will unify the treasury
bond registration, settlement, and clearance system this year.
</P>
<P>
China started issuing treasury bonds again in 1981 and its
annual issue has expanded greatly in recent years, hitting a
record 196 billion yuan last year. By the end of 1995, China had
issued 660 billion yuan in government bonds. Its bond issue this
year is budgeted at 248.596 billion yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
