<HEADLINE> Five Soccer Fans Killed in Stampede </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Five Nigerian soccer fans were
crushed to death inside locked doors of the National Stadium after
a World Cup Qualifying match here, according to the local
newspapers on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
And more than a dozen others fans were hospitalized in serious
condition at Lagos' University Teaching Hospital.
</P>
<P>
Only two of the five gates of the stadium were opened on
Saturday while more than 40,000 people trying to get out after the
Nigeria's 2-1 win over Guinea.
</P>
<P>
Crowds who were trying go out after the match were unaware the
door were still locked, so people were being trapped and
crushed. Stadium workers who were responsible for opening the
doors had abandoned their duties to celebrate Nigeria's victory,
according to the Lagos Guardian.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper also said more than the capacity of 40,000 people
were let into the game and that no crowd control measures were in
place.
</P>
<P>
It was the second such stampede at Lagos' National Stadium in
the last eight years. Eight fans and a player died in 1989 after a
World Cup qualifying match between Nigeria and Angola at the
stadium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
