<HEADLINE> Rebel Head Wants Peace Talk with Ugandan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Joseph Kony, the head of crippled
rebel Lord's Resistance Army (LRA), wants a peace talk with
Ugandan President Yoweri Moseveni, local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
Alfred James Obita, the LRA's secretary of external relation
and mass mobilization, when announcing the news at a conference
of Acholi tribe in London Saturday, asked Moseveni to first
express intention on the peace talk "in person, not by proxy".
</P>
<P>
The proposed face-to-face talk should be supervised by
international observers, he said.
</P>
<P>
Acholi tribe lives in northern Kitgum and Gulu districts where
LRA has conducted a ten-year guerrilla war against the Ugandan
government.
</P>
<P>
Obita made his remarks when LRA and other rebel groups in
Uganda are in trouble, according to a New Vision report.
</P>
<P>
LRA has three detachments now which has some 200 fighters
each, compared with some 2,000 soldiers in the past.
</P>
<P>
Kony has publicly abandoned the objective to overthrow Ugandan
government.
</P>
<P>
West Nile Bank Front, another rebel group, has lost its main
forces of more than 1,300 fighters in its fighting with Sudan
People's Liberation Army (SPLA) in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The allied democratic forces, also a rebel group, has lost its
main forces in fighting with Ugandan army since last November.
</P>
<P>
Alphonse Owiny Dollo, the state minister in charge of
pacification of the north, said at the conference that his
government will consider LRA's peace proposal when it stopped
killing and abduction in the north. 
</P>
</TEXT>
