<HEADLINE> Nigeria Produces 72.8 m Barrels of Oil in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Africa's largest oil producer
Nigeria produced 72.8 million barrels of crude oil in January,
averaging 2.3 million barrels a day, the Business Concord
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said the January production is 5.8 million barrels
or 8.7 percent more than that of December last year.
</P>
<P>
The country's export, however, dropped by 10.5 percent or 7.28
million barrels from December to 61.8 million barrels, or 1.99
million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted a Petroleum Ministry source as saying
that the production now is still within Nigeria's quota of 1.865
million barrels per day from the Organization of Petroleum Export
Countries.
</P>
<P>
The prices of Nigeria's major crude oil products, the Bonny
Light and Forcados depreciated further on the London market from
fortnight ago's 18.77 and 18.43 U.S. Dollars a barrel to last
weekend's 17.56 and 17.21 Dollars a barrel respectively.
</P>
<P>
The sliding oil price is becoming a serious threat to the
Nigerian government's budgetary revenue in 1997, which depends on
oil export for 90 percent of its foreign currency earnings and is
projected on the basis of 17 Dollars a barrel.  
</P>
</TEXT>
