<HEADLINE> Rwandan Ambassador to Tanzania Condemns Rwanda's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Mukanyange Joy, the Rwandan
Ambassador to Tanzania, has condemned the 1994 genocide in
Rwanda, describing it as a shame to Africans.
</P>
<P>
"What happened in Rwanda was a shame not only to Rwanda but
also to Africa in general", said Mukanyage in an interview
recently.
</P>
<P>
She challenged Tanzanians to take precautions in whatever they
do lest they find themselves in a situation similar to that of
Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
"Signs of civil strife start small but can grow tremendously
and lead to devastation", she warned, recalling that what
happened in Rwanda was a result of dictatorial politics.
</P>
<P>
She particularly admonished that tribalism and power-hungry
leaders could easily trigger a genocide. "Never let one group
rise over the other", she further warned.
</P>
<P>
Events that led to the mass political murders and genocide in
Rwanda were not clear to many people, she said, adding "It's not
because of tribal differences as many people tend to believe".
</P>
<P>
Mukanyange also suggested that the murders were a spontaneouss
reaction to the assassination of President Juvenal Habyarimana,
from the majority Hutu tribe, on April 6, 1994. 
</P>
