<HEADLINE> S. Africa, Angola in Coke Bottling Negotiation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Agreement on building a
20-million-U.S.-Dollar Coca-Cola bottling plant in Angola could
be reached between the Angolan government and a South African
Breweries (SAB) subsidiary within months,
</P>
<P>
"If everything goes according to plan, we should have an
agreement within three months," Richard Helmorem, the Central
Africa operations representative for Coke, was quoted by today's
Business Report daily newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
"After we have a deal it will take anywhere from 15 to 18
months to build the plant," he said.
</P>
<P>
SAB's offshore operation Indol International was negotiating
with Angola's Industry Ministry over percentage ownership in the
plant and Indol was likely to get a majority ownership, Helmore
said.
</P>
<P>
The plant, planned to be situated near Bom Jesus about 60
kilometers east of Luanda, would have initial capacity of six
million cases a year with expansion capability of up to 18
million cases a year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Prior to independence from Portugal in 1975, Angola had three
Coke plants respectively located in the capital of Luanda, the
central highlands city of Huambo and the coastal city of Lobito.
</P>
<P>
After the country's 20-year civil war, only the Huambo plant
remains operational.
</P>
<P>
The Huambo plant owned by the Angolan company Zuid has a
capacity of 240,000 cases a year and its franchise covers most of
central Angola. 
</P>
</TEXT>
