<HEADLINE> Basic Law Guarantees HK's Economic Success: HK Senior Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 7 (Xinhua) -- All key ingredients to Hong
Kong's economic success now were guaranteed from July 1 and
beyond in the Basic Law, Donald Tsang, Hong Kong's acting chief
secretary, said here today.
</P>
<P>
Tsang said that he believed that China would keep the promises
set out in the law.
</P>
<P>
At the Harvard Business School Alumni Conference on "Greater
China: Myths, Realities, Opportunities," Tsang said that the
reason for his faith in the Basic Law was that the Law was drafted
by the Chinese government over a period of five years with the
participation of a whole range of Hong Kong people.
</P>
<P>
He said that the promises it contains are not new requirements,
adding that they are based on Hong Kong's way of life now.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government created this blueprint for the Special
Administrative Region (SAR) of China because it could see how
successful Hong Kong is today and they want it to be just as
successful, and indeed more so, tomorrow," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong's continuing success will become a point of China's
national honor. Why then should China risk that success by going
back on its promises? I do not believe China will," Tsang said.
</P>
<P>
He said that "It is no-one's interests to renege on this
promise. The rule of law lies at the very heart of Hong Kong's
success. It plays a crucial role in securing and upholding the
prosperity and stability of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
On the myth that the press freedom and the free flow of
information generally would be eroded after 1997, Tsang said that
the government would not let these be eroded and again the Basic
Law makes a promise to this effect.
</P>
<P>
He added that Hong Kong was the telecommunications hub in the
Asia Pacific region and Hong Kong was linked to the rest of the
world by submarine cables, satellites and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Tsang also corrected the misconceptions held by some quarters
concerning the post-1997 law and order and corruption scene in
Hong Kong, as well as the alleged replacement of Hong Kong civil
servants with Beijing officials.  
</P>
</TEXT>
