<HEADLINE> Su-30s Being Inducted as Per Schedule: Indian Air </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 7 (Xinhua) -- India's Air Chief Marshal S.K.
Sareen said today that the induction of Suhoi-30 (Su-30) combat
jets from Russia was right on schedule and the first four had
reached India.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing modernization plan of the Indian air force which
includes induction of the Su-30 aircraft and upgradation of Mig-21
aircraft (Russia), was right on schedule, Sareen said while
inaugurating the week-long commanders' conference at the air
headquarters here.
</P>
<P>
India received four Su-30 K fighters in knocked-down condition
last month as part of the 63.3 billion rupees (1.783 billion US
dollars) aircraft deal with Russia under which a total of 40 Su-30
aircraft would be supplied by 2001. Future induction of the Su-30
combat jets would include the more sophisticated variants called
MK-1, MK-11 and MK-111 and the bomber version, he said.
</P>
<P>
The long-range, deep penetration supersonic Suhoi jets can
carry an enormous eight tons of armaments and rockets and can fly
upto over 5,000 km with one mid-air refueling.
</P>
<P>
India has the option to manufacture the Su-30s under license
after the delivery of the 40 jets, he further said.
</P>
<P>
The ageing Mig-21 "bis" warplanes are being currently upgraded
by Russia by installing sophisticated avionics and weapon systems.
Two Mig-21s were already in Russia for upgradation and another
over 120 planes would be upgraded in the next few years, he added.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
