<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong, United States Sign Air Services Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong-U.S. air services
agreement singed here today would provide a firm legal basis
for the continued development of air services between the two up
to and beyond June 30, 1997, a Hong Kong official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Stephen Ip, Hong Kong's Secretary for Economic Services, made
the comment at the signing ceremony here today.
</P>
<P>
Ip and Richard Boucher, the U.S. Consul-General in Hong Kong,
signed the document on behalf of their governments.
</P>
<P>
The regular air services between Hong Kong and the United
States started in 1937, when the Pan American established a
passenger and cargo flying services between California and Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
Nine U.S. airlines operate some 84 passenger and cargo services
per week to Hong Kong. They carried 920,000 passengers and
147,000 tons of air cargo on direct services in 1996 between Hong
Kong and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Cathay Pacific started its passenger and cargo services to the
U.S. in 1986, followed by Air Hong Kong, a dedicated air-cargo
carrier, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Cathay Pacific and Air Hong Kong now operate about 21 services
per week between Hong Kong and locals in the U.S. and in 1996,
they carried 315,000 passengers and some 42,000 tons of air cargo.
</P>
<P>
The total number of passengers carried on direct services alone
between Hong Kong and the U.S. by the airlines of both sides was
close to 1.2 million in 1996, a 12.7 percent increase over the
1995 figure.
</P>
<P>
Today's air services agreement is the 19th signed by Hong
Kong. Hong Kong has signed similar agreements with the
Netherlands, Switzerland, Canada, Brunei, France, New Zealand,
Malaysia, Brazil, Sri Lanka, Australia, Germany, the Republic of
Korea, Singapore, Japan, Italy, India, Myanmar and Thailand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
