<HEADLINE> Annan Favors Reform of U.N. Development Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 7 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary-General
Kofi Annan today stressed the need to reform the U.N. development
system in a bid to make it more efficient and cost-effective.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the inaugural session of the 12th Ministerial
Conference of the Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) Countries here, Annan
said the surest foundation for peace, stability and security is
economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
He said he intends to reform the role of the U.N. in
international cooperation for development and ensure that greater
resources are devoted to it.
</P>
<P>
To secure the development of developing countries, the U.N.
needs to re-examine constantly its means of attaining that
objective, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We need to ensure that our approach to development takes full
account of the economic, political and technological realities of
our times," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He said reforms should be taken to make the U.N. development
system sensitive to the concerns of developing countries so that
it can "provide assistance at the country level efficiently and
cost-effectively."
</P>
<P>
Talking about reform of the Security Council, he said that
"while an effective Security Council is vital for the U.N., a more
representative Security Council will enjoy even greater legitimacy
and support."
</P>
<P>
He hoped that one of the consequences of an expansion in the
council's membership would be to correct the under-representation
of developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers from nearly 70 NAM countries attend the
two-day ministerial meeting which was preceded by senior
officials' meeting on April 4-5. A final document and a New Delhi
declaration will be adopted at the end of the meeting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
