<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Declares Large Bank Notes Invalid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Iran (CBI) has
declared some Iranian big-valued bank notes invalid beginning
from May 22, the English daily Tehran Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by the CBI Sunday. The bank notes
with the face-value of 5,000 rials (1.66 U.S. dollars) and 10,000
rials (3.33 dollars), which are designed on both sides with
pictures of the Tehran refinery and the former site of the
Parliament, will be replaced at all banks as of April 6 in an
attempt to unify the different shapes of the old bank notes.
</P>
<P>
A statement released by the CBI called on people to refer
to all branches of banks throughout the country to convert their
old notes within the time span from April 6 to May 21.
</P>
<P>
The 10,000-rial note is the note of the biggest denomination
in the country. The counterfeit printing of these notes is
commonplace in Iran and the banks have to examine them carefully
before accepting them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
