<HEADLINE> Nigerians Suffer Iron Deficiency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 7 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey has shown that 25
percent of mothers and 29 percent of children in Nigeria suffer
from iron deficiency anemia (IDA), the Nigerian Tribune reported
today.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to curb the disease, the U.N. Children's Fund
(UNICEF) has begun the administration of iron tablets on 500,000
pregnant women in the country, said John Egbuta, the UNICEF
project officer, in charge of micro-nutrients in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The exercise, which started last month and is expected to cost
UNICEF about 10 million Naira (about 118,000 U.S. Dollars), is to
enrich expectant mothers with iron needed in the body.
</P>
<P>
The exercise, now being conducted in two government areas, is
targeted at about 10 million women and children.
</P>
<P>
It will cover all women of child-bearing age and children of
up to five years old when the second phase begins in July, the
UNICEF official said.
</P>
<P>
According to Egbuta, UNICEF is encouraging 1,500 schools in
Nigeria to cultivate gardens with vitamin A crops as part of the
diversification strategies being adopted.
</P>
<P>
Another strategy to be adopted is food fortification, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
