<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Current Account Surplus Up in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Japan's current account surplus
increased in February the second strait month by 15.4
percent from a year earlier to 865.2 billion yen (7.2 billion
U.S. dollars), the Japanese Finance Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
The current account surplus showed the second straight
year-on-year rise, following a 362.3 percent jump in January which
posted the first gain in 17 months.
</P>
<P>
The surplus in goods and services as a whole declined in
February by 4.8 percent to 363.3 billion yen (3 billion
U.S. dollars), the smallest surplus for February since 1985, the
ministry said in a preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
Japan's surplus in merchandise trade increased by 2.9 percent
to 878 billion yen (7.3 billion U.S. dollars). It is the first
year-on-year increase in 27 months.
</P>
<P>
Exports increased by 9.9 percent to 3,895.6 billion yen (32.5
billion U.S. dollars), up for the 19th consecutive month, while
imports increased by 12.2 percent to 3,017.7 billion yen (25.1
billion U.S. dollars), up for the 31th straight month, the
ministry said.
</P>
<P>
In services trade, Japan registered a deficit of 514.6 billion
yen (4.3 billion U.S. dollars), being widened by 9 percent from
a deficit of 472.1 billion yen (3.9 billion U.S. dollars) a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
The income account posted a surplus of 595.5 billion yen (5
billion U.S. dollars), compared with a 478.2 billion yen (4
billion U.S. dollars) surplus a year earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
