<HEADLINE> Jewish Settlers Try to Turn Army Bases into </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The major Israeli peace
organization Peace Now has revealed that Jewish settlers have
moved in three military outposts in the West Bank, hoping to
establish new settlements.
</P>
<P>
According to a Peace Now report distributed to the press
here, its activists discovered a third outpost, Nahal Plugot in
Gush Etzion, apart from the outpost of Ofri reported in the media
10 days ago, and Rehalim on the Jerusalem-Nablus highway
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The settlers at the outposts are bachelors, disclosed the
report. "It appears that the settlers have decided to use a
different strategy," said Peace Now spokeswoman Hagit Ya'ari.
</P>
<P>
However, the Council of Jewish Committees in Judea, Samaria,
(Jewish names for the West Bank) and Gaza, has flatly denied
reports of a building boom. "There is nothing new in the reports
about settlers living on military outposts, many have been living
in outposts for years," said council chairman Pinhas
Wallerstein.
</P>
<P>
In response to the charges, Avi Benayahu, Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai's media adviser, said Sunday night that in
accordance with the government decisions, no new settlements are
being established in Judea and Samaria.
</P>
<P>
Ten days ago, Israel Radio broadcast a report on settlers
living in shipping containers in Ofri.
</P>
<P>
After the Israel TV aired a program showing the containers in
which the settlers lived two days later, the police arrested the
settlers and detained them for questioning. At the time, the
council said it had no knowledge of the settlement.
</P>
<P>
An Ofri local official said the Ofri group consisted of three
or four young men who have been living on the hilltop for at
least a year.
</P>
<P>
Reports regarding Rehalim, near Shilo, claimed that the
council was attempting to change its status to a settlement. The
outpost was established six years ago.
</P>
<P>
Peace Now has announced to hold a demonstration at the
entrance to Sha'are Tikva this morning, to demand that the
government freeze construction in all settlements.
</P>
<P>
"The government has recently authorized the construction of an
additional 48 units at Sha'are Tikva," said Ya'ari, adding
that many of the existing units are still empty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
