<DOCNO> XIE19970407.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa in Danger of Greater Marginalization: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Sub-Sahara African continent
is in danger of being more marginalized in the long-term global
trends, according to a U.N. report issued recently.
</P>
<P>
The latest report compiled by the U.N. Industrial Development
Organization (UNIDO) urged Sub-Saharan countries to quicken the
tempo of economic reform in order to make themselves more
attractive to foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
It said that the continent's share of global manufacturing
output fell from a tiny 0.6 percent in 1970 to 0.3 percent in
1995.
</P>
<P>
The Sub-Sahara is losing export market share to Asian
countries even for the traditional commodities like cocoa,
coffee, vegetable oils, rubber and tin, it added.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that not a single African country is included
among the developing world's 12 targets for foreign capital.
</P>
<P>
All Sub-Saharan countries attract less than five percent of
the total 244 billion U.S. Dollars capital flow in the world.
</P>
<P>
However, a World Bank report said that Africa became more
attractive for foreign investors in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the report said, Sub-Saharan countries attracted a
total of 11.7 billion Dollars in private capital, a significant
increase over the 9.1 billion Dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Development aid from official sources totaled 15.3 billion
Dollars in 1996, a slight rise over the previous year, but less
than the 16.1 billion Dollars annual average during the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
According to the World Bank report, the region's debt
obligation continue to be more than twice the size of its yearly
export earnings with the ratio standing at 237 percent for 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970407.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
