<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia to Curb Illegal Timber Cutting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has
blacklisted 12 foreign companies from obtaining timber concession
licences for illegal cutting and exportation of timber, according
to today's Times of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper quoted Minister of Environment and Natural
Resources William Harrington as saying that the illegal cutting
and exportation of timber are particularly rampant in Western,
Southern and Luapula provinces.
</P>
<P>
The government will from now strictly scrutinize individuals
and companies applying for timber concession licences, said the
minister.
</P>
<P>
He said that only investors showing willingness and capacity
to add value locally to forestry industry and create employment
to Zambians and having afforestation programs as integral part of
the products will be considered for concession licences.
</P>
<P>
Harrington said the process of issuing concession licences is
being streamlined to ensure that only genuine investors are
allowed to engage in sustainable timber exploitation for the
benefit of present and future generations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
