<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Publishes Its First Grassland Atlas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- China's first grassland atlas has
been published, covering all aspects of China's 400 million-ha
grassland resources, according to the State Bureau of Surveying
and Mapping.
</P>
<P>
The atlas, published by the China Map Publishing House, is one
of the results of the nation-wide survey of grassland resources,
launched in 1979. The compilation work of the atlas had been going
on for ten years.
</P>
<P>
The atlas collected data from on-the-spot surveys of more than
100,000 plots of grassland across the country and the adoption of
recent satellite pictures. The atlas uses the scale of one to one
million and adopts middle-scale grassland maps of all the
administrative regions of the country.
</P>
<P>
It combines remote sensing technologies with on-the-spot survey
in map-making, and covers all the varieties, classifications, and
utilizations of various grasslands.
</P>
<P>
The maps of grasslands in the Taiwan Province were charted with
pictures from French SPOT and American TM satellites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
