<HEADLINE> Chinese Police Start to Patrol on Helicopters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Police in Wuhan, the capital of
central China's Hubei Province, have started to use helicopters to
combat severe criminal offenses, shoring up its "strike hard"
drive, the Legal Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The helicopters have been wielded as "a deterrent force"
against severe criminal offenders, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The Helicopter Unit of the Patrol Detachment of Wuhan Police
Bureau has been set up with permission from the city government,
it said.
</P>
<P>
"To date, the helicopters have been deployed successfully to
rescue hostages in a high rise and used to complete 15 major
missions since May 1995," it said.
</P>
<P>
Wang Yi of the Ministry of Public Security said in a telephone
interview that Wuhan has been the only city in the country whose
police use helicopters to crack down on crimes.
</P>
<P>
These 28D-FS police helicopters were a joint production by
Wuhan and a US company, he said, adding that it can fly at a
height of 4,000 meters, at a speed of 180 km per hour and for 500
km with no stops.
</P>
<P>
They are used in the city to help patrol streets, deploy police
forces, and provide telecommunications services, the Daily said.
</P>
<P>
The helicopters are especially effective in tracking criminals
and cars on the run, providing timely aid to the injured,
overseeing fires, floods and incidents, and coordinating with
ground police forces in their anti-crime fights.
</P>
<P>
Many police officers reached through telephone said that the
use of such helicopters may be spread in the future for its
speed and special functions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
