<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Use of Biogas Tanks Encouraged In Tanzania Rural </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 7 (Xinhua) -- A Morogoro-based
non-governmental organisation has installed 200 plastic
biodigesters in different households in Morogoro and Tanga
regions of eastern Tanzania, reducing the use of charcoal in the
households by 50 per cent.
</P>
<P>
The orgnisation, called the Foundation for Sustainable Rural
Development (SURUDE), has also managed to increase awareness on
environmental conservation and sustainable development among the
rural people in the regions.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Sarwatt, the project manager, said this here at the
weekend at a two-day national review workshop of Africa 2000
network programme, noting that SURUDE was fully involved in the
promotion of low cost plastic biodigesters.
</P>
<P>
Six seminars had been organised during which 240 farmers were
trained on the installation and maintenance of low cost plastic
biodigesters.
</P>
<P>
Some households in Turiani of Morogoro Region and Amani in
Tanga Region have so far benefitted from the project which aims
at improving the well-being of rural people through application
of appropriate technologies.
</P>
<P>
SURUDE formed by a group of farmers and technology developers
group in Turiani was registered three years ago.
</P>
<P>
The foundation was a beneficiary of the Africa 2000 network
programme having received financial assistance to the tune of
14,809,000 Tanzanian Shillings (about 24,680 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to Mr. Sarwatt, SURUDE had received requests for use
of biogas for lighting and was now studying the prospect of
implementing the idea using the low pressure gas.
</P>
<P>
SURUDE is ready to spread the activities in other areas in the
country where firewood is scarce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
