<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Tackles Mad Cow Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Uganda is monitoring all imported
products from Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy (BSE)-hit
countries to prevent the BSE-caused mad cow disease from
spreading to people and the cattle industry.
</P>
<P>
According to the local daily New Vision today, a national task
force on BSE has also been set up to coordinate with
international organizations and to advise government on policy
concerning the disease.
</P>
<P>
Winyi Kaboyo, Assistant Commissioner for Veterinary Public
Health in the Ministry of Health, was quoted as saying that
government was carrying out public education to explain its
policy in order to avoid misinformation and anxiety among the
people.
</P>
<P>
The mad cow disease is associated with a transmissible agent
consumed by cattle in concentrate feeds containing meat and bone
meal.
</P>
<P>
It was first reported in Britain in 1986 and increased
dramatically over the last ten years.
</P>
<P>
Over 163,000 BSE-infected animals have been found in Britain
ever since with 244 in Switzerland and a few others in nine other
countries.
</P>
<P>
None BSE case has been reported in Uganda or any other African
country.
</P>
<P>
BSE causes serious nervous disorders and eventually death.
There is no known cure yet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
