<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zaire's Lubumbashi City Governor Flees to Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Mwanza Ngoyi, Governor of Zaire's
second largest city Lubumbashi, has fled his war-torn country and
sought sanctury in Kitwe in Zambia's Copperbelt Province,
according to a report from Kitwe today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that most of guest houses in the city are full
of Zaireans, some of them paying U.S. Dollars for accommodation.
</P>
<P>
Ngoyi was quoted as saying on Sunday that the situation in
Lumbubashi is so tense that he has to run for his life and will
not go back if the tension is not eased in Zaire where Laurent
Kabila's rebel forces are advancing.
</P>
<P>
Another Zairean named Kalenga (one name) said that Kyungu
Wakumwanza, the former governor before Ngoyi, has been
re-appointed as Lubumbashi Governor.
</P>
<P>
Kalenga said that people are fleeing Lubumbashi although the
war has not yet reached the city.
</P>
<P>
Zaire's two warring sides started talks in South Africa in
search for national reconciliation but so far there is no sign
for a stop of the military strife in that central African
country. 
</P>
