<HEADLINE> S. Korean Parliament Committee Starts Hanbo Scandal Hearing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 7 (Xinhua) -- A special committee of the South
Korean National Assembly (parliament) investigating the Hanbo loan
scandal today starts a three-week-long hearing broadcast live over
suspects and 41 witnesses.
</P>
<P>
The committee is to question Hanbo Group Chairman Chung Tae-soo
in a Seoul prison on the names of politicians and officials he
bribed for the 6-billion-U.S. dollar preferential bank loan to his
subsidiary the Hanbo Steel Co.
</P>
<P>
The Hanbo Steel Co., the country's second largest steelmaker,
announced bankruptcy in January with debts reaching 5.8 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Chung has allegedly diverted some 1.7 billion U.S. dollars from
the 6-billion loan for lobbying and other purposes since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Opposition members of the committee reportedly are to grill
Chung on whether he supplied election campaign funds to President
Kim Young-sam, then candidate of the Democratic Liberal Party in
the 1992 presidential election, in exchange for the loan.
</P>
<P>
However, the committee's ruling party members hope the
three-week-long hearing will help dispel the opposition's attacks
on President Kim and the party as the attacks are believed to
exert a great influence on the presidential race at the end of
this year.
</P>
<P>
Those to be grilled include President Kim's second son Kim
Hyun-chul and three enjailed ruling and opposition legislators --
Hong In-kil, former senior secretary to President Kim, Kwon
Ro-kap, opposition leader Kim Dae-jung's right hand man, and Iiwang
Byung-tae, former National Assembly Finance-Economy Committee
Chairman.
</P>
<P>
Kim Hyun-chul was accused of meddling in important national
affairs by asking bank officials to extend the preferential loan
to Hanbo.
</P>
<P>
Han Lee-hun and Lee Suk-chae, former top economic advisors to
President Kim, who denied enjailed Hong In-kil's confession of
forcing bank officials to extend the loan to Hanbo at Hong's
request, are also to testify about their roles in the scandal at
the hearing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
