<HEADLINE> TB Cases Increase in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Tuberculosis cases have increased
rapidly and thus posed the greatest danger in Uganda, reported
the local daily New Vision today.
</P>
<P>
Over 113,152 new cases of TB have been reported in the last
five years in the country, compared with annually 5,000 cases in
1970s.
</P>
<P>
Crispus Kiyonga, Ugandan Minister of Health, was quoted as
saying that the figures only represent about half of the expected
TB annual case load.
</P>
<P>
He said TB, as the leading infection killer of adults today,
will kill at least three million people within the next ten years
if current trends continue.
</P>
<P>
"It is likely that no other infectious disease is creating as
many orphans and devastating as many families as TB," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
