<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Bipartisan Move to Solve Ethnic Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The understanding reached by the
exchange of letters between the ruling People's Alliance (PA)
President Chandrika Kumaratunga and the opposition United Notional
Party (UNP) leader Ranil Wickremasinghe last Thursday for solving
the ethnic conflict was welcomed by various sectors both at home
and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has long been plagued by problems between the
Sinhalese and Tamil, the major ethnic groups in the island
country.
</P>
<P>
The liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam has been fighting against
the government for a separate Tamil state in the North and east of
the country since 1983. More than 55,000 people have been killed
in the civil war.
</P>
<P>
Through the years the country's ethnic crisis could not be
resolved because the two main parties would not get together to
resolve the issue. But the exchange of letters is now seen as a
major achievement.
</P>
<P>
Almost in chorus, several groups, particularly the Tamils,
worst affected by the conflict, have welcomed the step. The
mainstream Tamil political parties see this as a positive move
towards peace.
</P>
<P>
The Peoples Liberation Organization, the Eelam Peoples
Democratic Party, the Eelam Peoples Revolutionary Liberation Front
and the Up Country Peoples Front have with one voice lauded the
accord between the PA and the UNP in approaching the ethnic issue.
</P>
<P>
The United Buddhist Clergy said that the agreement will receive
the blessings of all sections of the community.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming the move, the Sri Lanka Buddhist Congress has called
for wider cooperation among all political parties for resolving
all national issues and steering the country towards a more
vigorous path of development.
</P>
<P>
The Hindu Congress and the Hindu Council have applauded the
statesmanship of the two leaders on the bold step they had taken
which is worthy of the support of the people.
</P>
<P>
Several countries have also welcomed the step taken by the two
Sri Lankan leaders. Indian High Commissioner Nareshwal Dayal
Sunday said Delhi welcomed the step and supported a political
resolution to Sri Lanka's conflict.
</P>
<P>
The Australian government has hailed the agreement as having
the potential to provide the foundation for a just and equitable
solution to the ethnic conflict, Foreign Ministry sources here
said.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Britain and Germany have also praised the
accord between the two Sri Lankan parties, according to the
sources.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
