<HEADLINE> Tanzania, Uganda Committed to Tanga-Musoma Rail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania and Uganda have
renewed their commitment to building the Tanga-Arusha-Musoma
railway which has been on the drawing board for several years due
to lack of funds, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference shortly before ending the five-day visit
to Tanzania and flying home on Sunday, Ugandan Prime Minister
Kintu Musoke said that the two countries vowed also to implement
the proposed Dar es Salaam-Mwanza oil pipeline project.
</P>
<P>
The Kyotera-Mutukula-Mwanza project was also among priorities
which the two countries want to be implemented as soon as
possible so as to speed up their economic development and improve
people's living.
</P>
<P>
Musoke said feasibility study on the Tanga-Arusha-Musoma rail
project has been completed.
</P>
<P>
He said the two countries were seeking for funds, but he did
not tell how much the projects would cost.
</P>
<P>
Musoke said he was happy with efforts made in improving
services by the Dar es Salaam Port and the Tanzania Railway
Corporation (TRC) for smooth movement of goods to Uganda.
</P>
<P>
"Uganda is a land-locked country and it will thus exploit
every route available both through Kenya and Tanzania," he said.
</P>
<P>
He arrived in Tanzania on Wednesday, toured the Dar es Salaam
port, Zanzibar, TRC installations, Arusha-based East African
Cooperation Secretariat and the International Tribunal for
Rwanda.  
</P>
</TEXT>
