<HEADLINE> Canada Wins Women's Ice Hockey Championship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Canada overwhelmed the United
States 4-3 in the final to win its fourth straight gold medal in
the World Women's Ice Hockey Championship in Kitchener, Ontario on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Canadians have beaten the Americans for all four titles,
but this was the first in which they needed overtime.
</P>
<P>
The two teams played to a 3-3 draw at the regular three
periods.
</P>
<P>
Canada's Nancy Drolet scored the dicisive goal at 12:59 of
overtime and give Canada a 4-3 victory over the United States.
</P>
<P>
Drolet scored Canada's opening goal with 24 seconds left in the
first period. The U.S. team levelled in the second when Alana
Blahoski swatted the puck through goalie Lesley Reddon's pads and
it dribbled slowly over the line.
</P>
<P>
Canada led 2-1 two minutes later when Angela James' slap shot
bounced off a U.S. player and into the net. The U.S. team tied it
again when Stephanie O'Sullivan scooped a fluttering puck out of a
goalmouth scramble on a power play.
</P>
<P>
Drolet added the third by batting in a rebound over Whitten's
shoulder for a 3-2 lead. Less than three minutes later, the score
was tied again by U.S. forward Katie King.
</P>
<P>
Finland outclassed China 3-0 for the bronze medal, while Sweden
earned the fifth and final berth for the 1998 Olympics by beating
Russia 3-1. Switzerland edged Norway 1-0 in the seeding game.
</P>
<P>
Canada, the United States, Finland, China and Sweden will join
host country Japan in Nagano next winter at the first Olympic
women's ice hockey games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
