<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Step up Research of Ice Sheet on Antarctic Pole </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have completed
a survey of Antarctica and obtained more than 1,000 ice
cores and other samples.
</P>
<P>
These may help explain changes in the environment and climate
in Antarctica in the past 200 years.
</P>
<P>
Li Zhongqin, 35-year-old researcher at the Lanzhou Institute of
Glaciology and Cryopedology, attached to the Chinese Academy of
Sciences, said that it was the first time that Chinese scientists
investigated the ice sheet in the Antarctica and that they had
obtained precious ice core samples and materials.
</P>
<P>
Antarctica is the world's only continent without permanent
residents. It is also the region with lowest temperature, fastest
wind velocity, and the world largest ice sheet area.
</P>
<P>
Of Antarctica's 14 million square kilometers of the total land
space, 13.5 million square kilometers are covered with ice and
snow all year round.
</P>
<P>
Li said the survey, joined by more than 130 researchers from
China's 50 institutions, was China's 13th investigation tour in
Antarctica.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
