<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Thailand Needs to Boost "Stars" for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Thailand needs to further
stimulate exports of products in "rising star" categories while
placing priority on the poorly performing group, if the country is
to attain its 10 percent export growth target this year.
</P>
<P>
last year, Thailand's exports grew only 0.5 percent from 1995,
falling far short of the 18 percent growth target.
</P>
<P>
The country's highest expansion and highly competitive category
has 19 items, such as computers and parts, integrated circuits,
telecommunication equipment, electrical appliances, jewelry and
ornaments, electrical generators and motors, canned shellfish,
automobiles, motorcycles, animal feeds and cement.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe that this group still has good potential to
grow at a minimum of 10 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
To strengthen that growth, the government should ensure a
steady supply of raw materials, reducing tariffs on some imported
materials where necessary, to help companies lower production
costs.
</P>
<P>
The government can also help the sector deepen its development
in order to add value to products, particularly electrical and
electronic goods, and to upgrade the skills of the workforce.
</P>
<P>
The export value of this group last year was 677.8 billion baht
(27.1 billion US dollars), 49 percent of the total, up 12.2
percent on 1995.
</P>
<P>
The group's impressive growth was attributed to high
competitive capacity, introduction of medium-and high-technology
production machinery, the use of skilled labor and the increasing
relocation of foreign companies' production bases.
</P>
<P>
In order for the country to achieve the overall 10 percent
export growth target, even exports of goods in the so-called
problem sectors must grow at least by 3-4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the poorest performers with low competitive capacity
were garments, frozen seafood, footwear, plastic products,
fabrics, canned fish, synthetic thread, vehicle tyres, watches and
parts, frozen chicken, toys and artificial flowers.
</P>
<P>
This group's exports accounted for 329 billion baht (13.16
billion dollars), or 23.9 percent of the total exports, and
tumbled 21.7 percent compared with 1995.
</P>
<P>
Many products in this group have lost their edge to competitors
in lower-wage countries. As well, they often face non-tariff
barriers in export markets, such as environmental and sanitation
standards.
</P>
<P>
The government needs to place a priority on stimulating this
largely labor-intensive sector.
</P>
<P>
The second best performing group last year contained five
cyclical agricultural products: rubber, rice, sugar, tapioca
products and coffee. The group accounted for 169 million baht
(6.76 billion dollars) or 12.3 percent of the total export value,
up 4.8 percent on 1995. This sector also needs more technology to
increase production capacity and improve quality.
</P>
<P>
This group was followed by the "normal growth" sector, which
included oil products, canned fruits, and canned juice. They
accounted for 202 billion baht (8.08 billion dollars) or 14.7
percent of the total export value in 1996, up 3.5 percent on 1995.
</P>
<P>
It is widely believed that the country is now at a juncture for
economic structural adjustment, from labor-intensive economy to
technology-intensive economy, as labor and raw materials are
costing more than its low-income competitors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
