<HEADLINE> Political Mess Hits Blue Chips </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Uncertainty over the passage of
budget for 1997-98 in the wake of political mess at the Center
following the withdrawal of support of the Congress Party to the
United Front (UF) government dealt a severe blow to blue chips
which took a sharp beating during the week ended on April 4.
</P>
<P>
Although the equity market tried hard to override politics
through the mid week, the week ended with lackluster trading
performance, indicating another phase of uncertainty ahead.
Traders said that the worst thing was that the political onslaught
came at a moment when the underlying sentiment in the market had
started consolidating for a possible rally.
</P>
<P>
The Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) 30-share sensitive index
skidded 302.64 points, the fourth largest plunge ever, on last
Monday, after shedding a massive 344.63 points. The sensitive
index clawed back lost ground marginally in the hope of the
passage of the budget and stabilized at 355.07 from 3663.53 on
April 2 shedding a net 106.46 points.
</P>
<P>
Nervousness prevailed both in the National Stock Exchange (NSE)
and the Delhi Stock Exchange (DSE). The NSE 50-share index shed
5.80 points to 1001 points from 1057.87 points while the DSE index
dipped to 747.69 points from 769.14 points, a loss of 21.45
points.
</P>
<P>
The Congress withdrawal of support to the 10-month old United
Front (UF) government on last Sunday came as a rude shock to the
share market, whose sentiment took a tumble on the assumption that
the budget, which was hailed as historic by industry, would be put
on the backburner.  
</P>
</TEXT>
