<HEADLINE> Nepali Opposition Leader Warns of Constitutional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's main opposition leader
has warned that an ordinance issued recently for amending acts on
local bodies and their elections could lead to "constitutional
deadlock", the local press said today.
</P>
<P>
President of the Nepali Congress (NC) party Girija Prasad
Koirala told a press meet Sunday that the ordinance could lead to
constitutional crisis as the forthcoming local elections will be
held under the ordinance without parliamentary approval.
</P>
<P>
On the recommendation of the government, King Birendra Friday
issued the ordinance to amend the country's acts concerning local
administrations bodies and elections.
</P>
<P>
The ordinance came out soon after the parliament concluded its
winter session without passing the bills, including the one on
decentralization, which earlier were expected to be passed.
</P>
<P>
The decentralization bill is designated to give more autonomous
rights to the local administration bodies and to empower local
people.
</P>
<P>
According to the opposition leader, the ordinance have to be
approved by both houses of the parliament within six months of its
issuance under the constitution.
</P>
<P>
However, the government has decided to hold the local elections
by mid-June on the schedule set by the former NC-led government.
</P>
</TEXT>
