<HEADLINE> Accused in Stock Market Scandal Granted Bail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The high court of Bangladesh on
Sunday granted anticipatory bail to some 20 alleged stock market
manipulators while hundreds of small investors demonstrated
demanding their trial by special tribunals.
</P>
<P>
Those who were granted bails when they surrendered before the
court in connection with the stock market case included Dhaka
Stock Exchange (DSE) Chairman Imtiyaz Hussain and some directors
of different companies.
</P>
<P>
A magistrate on April 2 issued warrants of arrests against 32
people, who were accused of manipulating the share market during a
bull run last year by fraudulent means.
</P>
<P>
On the next day, four leading businessmen of Bangladesh, who
are involved with the case, secured anticipatory bail form the
high court.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government has imposed a ban on foreign travel
by all the accused in this biggest share market scandal in
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, a few hundred kerb traders also staged a noisy
demonstration in front of the DSE building, blaming the accused
for manipulating a market bubble which saw the DSE index rise from
900 to 3700 point in the second half of last year.
</P>
<P>
These angry small investors strongly demanded trial by special
tribunals of those responsible for the share market scandal and
also burnt effigies of some of the accused. 
</P>
