<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Sugar Output to Fall for Labor Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's sugar production of
this season may fall 10 percent short of target as many sugarcane
planters are burning their fields to make harvesting easier.
</P>
<P>
About 80 percent of the country's sugarcane farmers are burning
their cane because of shortage of labor, according to cane and
sugar board office Secretary-General Pramode Vidtayasuk.
</P>
<P>
Burning up cane leaves and grass in the fields makes cane
cutting and transport easier but also reduces cane weight.
</P>
<P>
Cane-burning is not practiced in the northeast, where cheap
migrant labor is available.
</P>
<P>
Sugar output is expected to total 5.5 million tons this year,
of which 4 million is earmarked for export.
</P>
<P>
Many cane planters seek jobs at construction sites in big
cities during slack season, and will not return home to cut his
cane because they earn much more in cities. They simply send money
back to employ others to cut their cane.
</P>
<P>
Each year about 100,000 laborers are employed during the cane
harvesting season.
</P>
<P>
The cane and sugar board office hopes to reduce the practice
for the next milling season.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970407.0169 </DOCNO>
