<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Launch Its Third Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's third satellite,
Thaicom 3, is due for launch from French Guiana on Saturday,
according to a source at Shinawatra Satellite Plc, the operator of
the Thai satellite.
</P>
<P>
The new satellite is scheduled to be launched into the 78.5
degrees east position, the same orbit as currently used by Thaicom
1, which is to be shifted to 120 degrees east to make way for
Thaicom 3.
</P>
<P>
However, Thaicom 3 will be close to the 80 degrees east slot
used by the Russian satellite, Express, and will have a frequency
interference problem.
</P>
<P>
The Russian satellite and Thaicom 1 have not interfered each
other because their footprints are different.
</P>
<P>
But the footprint of Thaicom 3 will extend to cover India,
overlapping that of the Express satellite.
</P>
<P>
Equipment would need to be adjusted to solve the problem, said
the source, adding that Russia wanted Shinawatra to shoulder all
the expenses as the Express satellite was in place first.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will have four weeks to solve the footprint
overlap after Thaicom 3's launch, as tests will be needed before
Thaicom 3 enters its planned orbital position.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
