<HEADLINE> East China City Improves Use of Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Zibo city, a manufacturing center in
east China's Shandong Province, spent most of its overseas
investment developing local industries.
</P>
<P>
The city brought in 250 million US dollars of contracted
overseas investment last year, down eight percent from the
previous year, according to the City Commission of Foreign Trade
and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
However, 87 percent was used for local industrial projects, an
official of the commission said.
</P>
<P>
The official said that more than 37 percent of the total
overseas funds last year was invested in pillar industries such as
machinery, building materials, chemicals, electronics, and
textiles.
</P>
<P>
The city added 87 foreign-funded projects last year. The
average overseas investment in each project soared 37 percent over
the year 1995 to exceed 2.37 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Twelve overseas-funded projects each involved investment over
five million US dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investment from Asia, Europe, and the United States is
flowing into the city.
</P>
<P>
Local foreign-funded enterprises exported 109 million US
dollars worth-of goods last year, rising 51 percent over 1995, and
contributing 24 percent to the city's total earnings from
exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
