<HEADLINE> Indonesia's "Comfort Women" to Sue over Compensation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of Indonesian women
forced into prostitution by the Japanese army during World War II
plan to sue the government over its plan to keep their
compensation money, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Budi Hartono, chairman of the Legal Aid Foundation (IBH) in the
central Java town of Yogyakarta, said on Saturday that the
preparations for the lawsuit were almost complete.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government agreed last year to pay the 249 former
so-called comfort women 9 billion rupiah (3.7 million US dollars
as compensation for their sexual slavery during the imperial
army's occupation of Indonesia between 1942 and 1945.
</P>
<P>
Tokyo said it would hand the money over to Indonesia's Social
Affairs Ministry, but in January, Social Affairs Minister Inten
Suweno said the government would actually use the cash to build an
old people's home.
</P>
<P>
Harsono said his clients last Wednesday sent a letter to
President Soeharto asking for their compensation money.
</P>
<P>
"If we get no response, we will launch the suit," Hartono said.
</P>
</TEXT>
