<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Resuming of University Enrollment Fruitful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The resumption of the university
enrollment system has been a major factor for the country's
economic growth over the past two decades, according to Chinese
officials.
</P>
<P>
Ten million people have graduated from Chinese universities
since the enrollment system was resumed in 1977, and they have
been making great contributions to China's modernization drive,
the State Education Commission said today.
</P>
<P>
Chinese universities stopped recruiting students during the
Cultural Revolution (1966-76), when knowledge was viewed as a
accoutrement of the exploiting class and bourgeoisie.
</P>
<P>
The resumption began in 1977 when the late leader Deng Xiaoping
gave a keynote speech calling for the revival of education and
science.
</P>
<P>
In 1977, Chinese universities recruited the first group of
students after the Cultural Revolution, and 5.7 million people
registered for the entrance examination.
</P>
<P>
The country is carrying out a program to reform the higher
learning sector-- asking students to pay for themselves and
encouraging them to find jobs by themselves.
</P>
<P>
Previously, the state subsidized all the tuition fees for the
students and assigned jobs to the graduates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970407.0197 </DOCNO>
