<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fresh Riot Shakes Pekalongan, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- A fresh riot shook Indonesia's
central Java town of Pekalongan Sunday, but the situation was soon
put under control by security authorities, according to reports
reaching here early this morning.
</P>
<P>
Early Sunday morning, an angry mob of about 350 people went on
the rampage, looting a motorcycle shop and setting fire to at
least nine motorcycles and a truck, said the reports.
</P>
<P>
A number of shops on the street of Urip Sumoharjo were stoned
and destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Order was restored seven hours later by troops from the 0710
regional military command and local policemen.
</P>
<P>
The rioting was triggered by a report that a United Development
Party (PPP) supporter was stabbed to death by an unknown
assailant.
</P>
<P>
Police were investigating the incident, which appeared to be
linked to rioting which occurred there two weeks ago, reports
said.
</P>
<P>
Last week, 30 people were sentenced to prison terms ranging
from three days to three months for their involvement in the March
26 riot when a number of shops and properties were vandalized.
</P>
<P>
The riot started when PPP flags around a music concert area
were removed by supporters of the ruling party Golkar.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's three political parties -- Golkar, PPP and the
Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI) are preparing for the May 29
general election.
</P>
<P>
The three parties are vying for 425 seats of the house of
representatives in the election during which more than 120 million
people are eligible to vote.
</P>
<P>
Pekalongan was the only central Java city where Golkar lost to
PPP in the 1992 elections.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
