<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek, Cypriot Parliament Speakers Meet in Athens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 6 (Xinhua) --Greek Parliament Speaker Apostolos
Kaklamanis met with his Cypriot counterpart Spyros Kyprianou here
today to discuss issues of their common interest.
</P>
<P>
The two told the press after the meeting that they exchanged
views on developments of the Cyprus issue and goals of the two-day
conference which is being held here and attended by speakers of the
Mediterranean parliaments.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on a statement by U.S. ambassador to Greece Thomas
Niles today that Washington would interfere if Athens and Ankara
were led to an armed conflict in the Aegean, Kaklamanis called the
statement as "nothing new", adding that a U.S. political decision
leading to positive developments in the Cyprus and the Aegean
issues would be important.
</P>
<P>
"In other words," he said, "the United States must feel the
need for Turkey to change its attitude."
</P>
<P>
Kaklamanis stressed that nothing had yet changed regarding the
existence of "a real threat" in the Aegean.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Mustafa Kalemli, president of the
Turkish National Assembly, today also said at the Mediterranean
parliaments conference that there was no tension between Turkey
and Greece.
</P>
<P>
He called on polititians in both countries to work in a climate
of mutual understanding and good will in order to establish a good
bilateral ties between Athens and Ankara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
