<HEADLINE> BBC War Correspondent Named Anti-Sleaze Candidate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Martin Bell, the well-known BBC war
correspondent, has agreed to stand as an independent anti-sleaze
candidate to fight against a Conservative candidate, who is
accused of taking money for parliamentary questions.
</P>
<P>
Britain's two main opposition Labor and Liberal Democrat
parties have backed Bell as their joint election candidate in an
effort to unseat Conservative candidate Neil Hamilton, who has
denied cash-for-question allegation, according to a BBC television
report.
</P>
<P>
Bell, who has reported on wars for 30 years, will replace Labor
candidate Jon Kelly and Liberal Democrat Roger Barlow in Tatton
constituency in northwest England unless Hamilton agrees not to
stand in the coming election.
</P>
<P>
Hamilton, a former government minister, reportedly had a strong
majority of 15,860 in the 1992 election, making Tatton one of
Conservatives' safest seat in the May 1 general election.
</P>
<P>
An opinion poll, conducted by the Observer newspaper, suggested
that a high-profile anti-sleaze candidate could eventually defeat
Hamilton. 
</P>
</TEXT>
