<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Small Exporters Remain Confused over EMU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Britain's small exporters remained
confused about the prospect of the European Monetary Union (EMU)
with less than a third supporting its introduction on January 1
1999, according to a latest poll.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by Euro Sales Finance, indicated that
although those British exporters polled all have a vested interest
in European transactions, only 27 percent of them are in favor of
the single European currency named euro.
</P>
<P>
Most of those surveyed are not convinced that the single
currency would be launched on time, although more than half of
those people agree that the EMU would make exporting easier and 44
percent believe it would strengthen trading relations.
</P>
<P>
More than half of the small exporters said that the big
drawback with the introduction of a single currency was the loss
of sovereignty, although 36 percent said they did not know whether
this was going to be a problem.
</P>
<P>
Ian Fitz-Harris, chief executive of Euro Sales Finance, said:
"Most of our clients like the idea of monetary union in principle,
but at the moment they are fairly cynical about the whole subject.
They do not think it is going to happen."
</P>
<P>
"Politicians sowing the seeds of doubt about the EMU have done
businessmen a disservice. Exporting companies should be preparing
for the EMU not ignoring it," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
